{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3323735,"name":"","username":"DataChaos","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/d/71e660/{size}.png","created_at":"2024-03-04T20:29:55.623Z","cooked":"<p>Hello everyone, I’m having an issue with SparkPIDController on an arm. A through bore encoder is mounted on our arm, which is wired into the Spark Max using an absolute encoder adapter. When I setReference using the position controller to a value of 0.85 (the reading when the arm is up) with the values the arm moves to 0.99 accurately and stays there. As you can tell, 0.99 is not 0.85. When I increase the set point to 1, the arm starts oscillating at the same point instead of moving to a different location. When I decrease the set point, nothing special seems to happen.</p>
<p>Here’s the basic ArmSubsystem I’ve set up.</p>
<details>
<summary>
ArmSubsystem</summary>
<pre data-code-wrap="java"><code class="lang-java">public class ArmSubsystem extends SubsystemBase {
    private final CANSparkMax armMotor1;
    private final CANSparkMax armMotor2;
    private final AbsoluteEncoder armEncoder;
    private final SparkPIDController armPidController;

    public ArmSubsystem(int armMotor1Id, int armMotor2Id) {
        armMotor1 = new CANSparkMax(armMotor1Id, MotorType.kBrushless);
        armMotor2 = new CANSparkMax(armMotor2Id, MotorType.kBrushless);
        armMotor1.restoreFactoryDefaults();
        armMotor2.restoreFactoryDefaults();
        armMotor2.follow(armMotor1, true);
        armEncoder = armMotor1.getAbsoluteEncoder(Type.kDutyCycle);
        armPidController = armMotor1.getPIDController();
        armPidController.setFeedbackDevice(armEncoder);
        armPidController.setPositionPIDWrappingEnabled(false);
        armPidController.setP(0.1);
        armPidController.setI(0);
        armPidController.setD(0.02);
        armPidController.setFF(0.03);
        armMotor1.burnFlash();
        armMotor2.burnFlash();
    }
    // ..
}
</code></pre>
